def graph (start, stop, data,scale,divisor,mu, convolutions, xmax = None,xmin = None, averageMax = None, xlabel = None, ylabel = None, title = None):
        
    if (xmax == None):
        xmax = stop
    if (xmin != None):
        start = xmin
    # Graphs the initiall distribution
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1)
    if averageMax != None:
        plt.step(x=np.linspace(start,averageMax,xmax-start), y = data[start:xmax], where = 'mid')
        x = np.linspace(start, averageMax, 10000)
        ax.plot(x,scipy.stats.norm.pdf(x,scale = scale, loc = mu)/divisor,linewidth = 3,alpha = 0.7) # 6.1 fits the curve to the distribution
    
    else:
        plt.step(x=np.linspace(start,xmax,xmax-start), y = data[start:xmax], where = 'mid')
        x = np.linspace(start, xmax, 10000)
        ax.plot(x,scipy.stats.norm.pdf(x,scale = scale, loc = mu * (convolutions+1))/divisor,linewidth = 3,alpha = 0.7) # 6.1 fits the curve to the distribution
    
    if xlabel == None:
        plt.xlabel("Signal measured", fontsize = 18)
    else:
        plt.xlabel(xlabel, fontsize = 18)
    if ylabel == None:
        plt.ylabel("Probability of occuring", fontsize = 18)
    else:
        plt.ylabel(ylabel, fontsize = 18)
    if title == None:
        plt.title("Distribution", fontsize = 22)
    else:
        plt.title(title, fontsize = 22)
    plt.show()

    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1)
    if averageMax != None:
        plt.step(x=np.linspace(start,averageMax,xmax-start), y = data[start:xmax], where = 'mid')
        x = np.linspace(start, averageMax, 10000)
        ax.plot(x,scipy.stats.norm.pdf(x,scale = scale, loc = mu)/divisor,linewidth = 3,alpha = 0.7) # 6.1 fits the curve to the distribution
    
    else:
        plt.step(x=np.linspace(start,xmax,xmax-start), y = data[start:xmax], where = 'mid')
        x = np.linspace(start, xmax, 10000)
        ax.plot(x,scipy.stats.norm.pdf(x,scale = scale, loc = mu * (convolutions+1))/divisor,linewidth = 3,alpha = 0.7) # 6.1 fits the curve to the distribution
    if xlabel == None:
        plt.xlabel("Signal measured", fontsize = 18)
    else:
        plt.xlabel(xlabel, fontsize = 18)
    if ylabel == None:
        plt.ylabel("Probability of occuring", fontsize = 18)
    else:
        plt.ylabel(ylabel, fontsize = 18)
    if title == None:
        plt.title("Semilog distribution", fontsize = 22)
    else:
        plt.title(title + " (semilog)", fontsize = 22)
    plt.semilogy()
    plt.show()

for i in range(25):
    base_poisson[i] = scipy.stats.poisson.pmf(i, 3)

B) After 5 days the summed probability distribution is still Poisson¶

In [11]:
convolved_bins = base_poisson
for i in range(5):
    convolved_bins = np.convolve(convolved_bins, base_poisson)
In [12]:
graph(0,len(convolved_bins), convolved_bins,4.2,1,x, 5,xmax = 50, title = " 5 Day summation")

While the standard plot can lead one to believe that the distribution is gaussian, we can see from the semilog-y plot the telltale signs of a Poisson distribution. this is shown in the sharp rise from the left towards the mean, with a more gradual falloff as the signal meassured goes to the right, as opposed to the parabolic nature of the gaussian curve.

In [17]:
convolved_bins_200 = base_poisson
for i in range(200):
    convolved_bins_200 = np.convolve(convolved_bins_200, base_poisson)
In [18]:
graph(0,len(convolved_bins_200), convolved_bins_200, 0.15,164,x, 200, averageMax = 25, title = "200 Day Average")

Here we see an extremely sharp peak around the mean, with very little distribution away from it. From this we can deduce that as we continue to increase the number of convolutions, we see that the average begins to narrow in on the $\mu$ from the Poisson distribution equation. In addition, it starts to resemble more and more a gaussian with a very small standard deviation. This is the key to relating to part B. The Poisson distribution still is the deciding factor over what the average will look like, but in only so much as the mean of the average. While yes there is an influence on the shape, we can see the shape begin to look less and less like a Poisson distribution and more and more like a gaussian, which follows the central limit theorem.

Problem 2¶

A) How the distribution changes¶

In [23]:
bins = [-1]*201
start = -1
for i, end in zip(range(201), np.linspace(0,8.2,201)):  # This is limited to 8.2 since after this, the numbers are too small to subtract traditionally
    bins[i] = scipy.stats.rayleigh.cdf(end) - scipy.stats.rayleigh.cdf(start)
    start = end
rayleigh_base = bins[1:]  # slices off bin from 0 to 0
In [24]:
graph(0,len(rayleigh_base), rayleigh_base, 0.8,20,1, 1, averageMax = 8.2, title = "Rayleigh Distribution")
In [68]:

In [141]:
graph(0,len(convolved_rayleigh), convolved_rayleigh, 0.016, 45000, 1.241, 20, averageMax = 8.2, title = "Rayleigh Distribution After 2000 Convolutions")

B) Discuss how the shape changes¶

While it is very difficult to see, the distribution does become more gaussian as we continue to average it with itself. However with this distribution and method used in particular, we can actually see that the convolution doesn't seem to approach the gaussian as quickly as expected. After around 20 averages, we begin to see that the shape is gaussian-like, although fairly far off. After 2000, we see a very gaussian curve however, this distribution will never truly become a gaussian, according to the central limit theorem, as infinite convolutions are needed for a true gaussian. However, it can continue to approach a gaussian distribution with increasing accuracy.

Probability: 	4.822114160655337e-06
Sigma: 		4.425

Following the directions as written, I chose a gaussian distribution with a width of 2. The floating point signal that I chose was a signal of 8.85. This gave a probability of roughy $4.82 \times 10^-6$, thus giving a sigma of 4.425. This is however not significant enough to be reported, as the minimum needed is 5 sigma.

B)¶

Statistical Question¶

If I have a signal candidate of 8.85, what is the probability that a signal of this strength or higher was not generated by the background?

B) Significance of meassurement¶

In [33]:
trial_factor = 10000
scipy.stats.norm.isf(probability*trial_factor)
Out[33]:
1.6623516704296202

Here, I multiplied the probability by the number of events that occured to see the total probability of meassuring this value or higher. Then, I took the isf of it to find the sigma value of the probability.

Problem 4¶

A) 5-sigma detection in version 1¶

In [34]:
sigma_5 = scipy.stats.norm.sf(5)
scipy.stats.norm.isf(sigma_5, scale = 2)
Out[34]:
10.000000000000002

A 5 sigma distiribution would have a probability of $2.8 \times 10^{-7}$, which when the probability distribution has a width of 2, we see that the corrosponding value needed to achive 5 sigma is 10.

B) 5-sigma detection in version 2¶

In [35]:
scipy.stats.norm.isf(1/(3500000*trial_factor), scale = 2)
Out[35]:
13.102053310128698

C) Discoverey with a trials factor of 10k¶

For a sigma event to occur, we would expect a signal of at least 13.1 to occur given our background distribution. This is higher than the previous 5-sigma event, since there is a chance to measure a 5-sigma event simply from the backgroun distribution itself. Taking this into account, we see that we now have a higher bar to clear in order to meassure an event of significance.

D) Much higher trial factor 5-sigma threshold¶

In [36]:
trial_factor = 50000000000000 #50,000,000,000,000
scipy.stats.norm.isf(1/(3500000*trial_factor), scale = 2)
Out[36]:
18.643780640009368

Even with a trial factor of $5 \times 10^{13}$, we still only see the minimum for a 5 sigma event at a relatively low number of 18.64. While the trial factor went up by 9 orders of magnitude, the 5 sigma point only went up by about 50%
